# Understanding hashCode() and equals():
    Imagine you’re building a student tracking app for your classroom. You’ve added profiles of students like Ravi (ID: 101).
    Later, when Ravi logs in again with the same name and ID, your app checks if he's already registered. Surprisingly,
    your app says: “Student not found.”

    You double-check the data. Everything matches. So why is this happening?

    Just like in real life where we identify people based on names and IDs, Java needs a way to understand whether two objects
    are “the same.” But by default, Java doesn't compare what's inside the objects — it compares where they live in memory.

    To make sure Java compares objects based on their data, we need to use two methods: equals() and hashCode().

Q1. What Are equals() and hashCode()?
Standard Definitions
    1. equals() is a method that checks if two objects have the same information inside them — like the same name and ID.
    2. hashCode() is a method that gives each object a number that helps Java quickly find and organize it in collections like HashSet or HashMap.

Simple Explanation:
    Think of storing student records in a digital cupboard.
        1. equals() is like comparing two student forms to see if they have the same details — same name, same ID.
        2. hashCode() is like checking which drawer the form should be kept in.

    Even if two forms have the same details, if they’re placed in different drawers, the system won’t realize
    they belong to the same student. That’s why both equals() and hashCode() must work together —
    so the system knows what to compare and where to look.

Q2. Why Are These Methods So Important?
    Making Sure Items Are Not Repeated
    In Java, tools like HashSet, HashMap, and LinkedHashSet are used to store items. But they need to know two things:
        1. Where to keep each item — this is decided by hashCode().
        2. Whether the item is already there — this is checked using equals().

    If either of these methods is missing or not written correctly, Java might treat two identical items as different.
    This can lead to duplicates or make the program unable to find an item that was already added. That’s why both
    methods are important for keeping your data clean and accurate.

# Overriding hashCode() and equals() in Custom Objects:
    When using sets like HashSet or LinkedHashSet to store custom objects (such as instances of a custom class),
    you need to override both hashCode() and equals() methods to ensure proper functioning.
    Let’s understand why this is important and how to do it correctly.

# The Problem Without Overriding
    Imagine you’re building a feature in the Kodnest app to store student profiles. If you don’t override hashCode() and equals(),
    Java will use the default implementations provided by the Object class. This means that each object’s hashCode() will be
    based on memory address, and equals() will simply check for reference equality.
            Set<Student> set = new HashSet<>();
            set.add(new Student("Ravi", 101));
            set.add(new Student("Ravi", 101));
            System.out.println(set.size()); // Output: 2 ❌

    This set should store only unique students. But because we didn’t override equals() and hashCode(),
    Java treats both students as different — even if their data is the same.

Q3. How to Override hashCode() and equals()?
    To make sure HashSet or LinkedHashSet can correctly determine the uniqueness of custom objects,
    you need to override both hashCode() and equals() methods.

        import java.util.Objects;

        public class Student {
            String name;
            int id;

            public Student(String name, int id) {
                this.name = name;
                this.id = id;
            }

            @Override
            public boolean equals(Object obj) {
                if (this == obj) return true;
                if (obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;
                Student s = (Student) obj;
                return id == s.id && name.equals(s.name);
            }

            @Override
            public int hashCode() {
                return Objects.hash(name, id);
            }
        }
    Now when you add the same student twice:
        Set<Student> set = new HashSet<>();
        set.add(new Student("Ravi", 101));
        set.add(new Student("Ravi", 101));
        System.out.println(set.size()); // Output: 1 ✅

    Now, when you add the same student again, Java checks the data using equals() and looks in the right place using hashCode().
    Since both the name and ID match, Java understands it's the same student and does not add it again to the set.

# Key Points to Remember:
    1. Java collections like HashSet use hashCode() to find items quickly.
    2. They use equals() to check whether two objects are actually the same.
    3. If two objects are equal, they must return the same hash code.
    4. When using custom classes in hash-based collections, always override both methods.
    5. Objects.hash() is a simple way to generate a proper hash code.

# Common Interview Questions and Answers:
    Q1. What is the purpose of the equals() method in Java?
    Answer: The equals() method checks whether two objects have the same data. It’s used to compare the values inside the objects, not their memory location.

    Q2. What does the hashCode() method do?
    Answer: The hashCode() method returns a number (called a hash code) that helps Java store and find objects quickly in collections like HashSet or HashMap.

    Q3. Why should we override both equals() and hashCode()?
    Answer: If you override only one, collections may not work correctly. For example, two objects might be equal based on their data,
            but if their hash codes are different, a set or map might store them separately. To avoid issues like duplicates or
            missing data, both methods must be overridden together.

    Q4. What happens if two equal objects have different hash codes?
    Answer: Java will treat them as different in hash-based collections, which can lead to duplicates or make it impossible
            to find an object even though it was added earlier.













